\title{Sicp}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{description}{"SICP: Structure and Interpretation of Computer Programs - computational processes, abstraction, and metalinguistic design"}

\subtree{
\title{SICP Skill}
\blockquote{*"Programs must be written for people to read, and only incidentally for machines to execute."* — Abelson & Sussman}

\p{Geometric morphism translation from sicp.info preserving the hierarchical node structure as an ACSet with GF(3) coloring for trifurcated processing.}

\subtree{
\title{Overview}
\p{\strong{Structure and Interpretation of Computer Programs} (Second Edition) by Harold Abelson and Gerald Jay Sussman, with Julie Sussman Foreword by Alan J. Perlis © 1996 Massachusetts Institute of Technology}

\p{The wizard book for computational thinking—procedures as abstractions, data as abstractions, and the interpreter as the ultimate abstraction.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Chapters}
\subtree{
\title{Chapter 1: Building Abstractions with Procedures [PLUS]}
\ul{
\li{\strong{1-1}: The Elements of Programming (expressions, naming, evaluation)}
\li{\strong{1-2}: Procedures and the Processes They Generate (recursion, iteration, orders of growth)}
\li{\strong{1-3}: Formulating Abstractions with Higher-Order Procedures (λ, returned values)}
}

\p{Key concepts: Substitution model, lexical scoping, fixed points, Newton's method}
}

\subtree{
\title{Chapter 2: Building Abstractions with Data [ERGODIC]}
\ul{
\li{\strong{2-1}: Introduction to Data Abstraction (rational numbers, barriers)}
\li{\strong{2-2}: Hierarchical Data and the Closure Property (sequences, trees, picture language)}
\li{\strong{2-3}: Symbolic Data (quotation, differentiation, sets, Huffman encoding)}
\li{\strong{2-4}: Multiple Representations for Abstract Data (tagged data, data-directed programming)}
\li{\strong{2-5}: Systems with Generic Operations (type coercion, symbolic algebra)}
}

\p{Key concepts: Pairs, cons/car/cdr, closure property, abstraction barriers, message passing}
}

\subtree{
\title{Chapter 3: Modularity, Objects, and State [PLUS]}
\ul{
\li{\strong{3-1}: Assignment and Local State (set!, costs of assignment)}
\li{\strong{3-2}: The Environment Model of Evaluation (frames, procedure objects)}
\li{\strong{3-3}: Modeling with Mutable Data (queues, tables, digital circuits, constraints)}
\li{\strong{3-4}: Concurrency: Time Is of the Essence (serializers, deadlock)}
\li{\strong{3-5}: Streams (delayed evaluation, infinite streams, signal processing)}
}

\p{Key concepts: State, identity, time, streams vs objects duality}
}

\subtree{
\title{Chapter 4: Metalinguistic Abstraction [PLUS]}
\ul{
\li{\strong{4-1}: The Metacircular Evaluator (eval/apply, syntax procedures, environments)}
\li{\strong{4-2}: Variations on a Scheme (lazy evaluation, normal vs applicative order)}
\li{\strong{4-3}: Variations on a Scheme: Nondeterministic Computing (amb, backtracking)}
\li{\strong{4-4}: Logic Programming (unification, pattern matching, query systems)}
}

\p{Key concepts: eval/apply loop, special forms, thunks, amb evaluator, Prolog-style logic}
}

\subtree{
\title{Chapter 5: Computing with Register Machines [ERGODIC]}
\ul{
\li{\strong{5-1}: Designing Register Machines (data paths, controllers, subroutines)}
\li{\strong{5-2}: A Register-Machine Simulator (the machine model, assembler)}
\li{\strong{5-3}: Storage Allocation and Garbage Collection (vectors, stop-and-copy)}
\li{\strong{5-4}: The Explicit-Control Evaluator (machine code for Scheme)}
\li{\strong{5-5}: Compilation (structure of compiler, lexical addressing, interfacing)}
}

\p{Key concepts: Register allocation, continuation-passing, tail recursion, compilation}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{GF(3) Conservation}
\p{The Info file nodes distribute perfectly across GF(3) trits:}

\pre{\startverb
Total nodes: 138
MINUS (-1):  46  ████████████████
ERGODIC (0): 46  ████████████████
PLUS (+1):   46  ████████████████
Sum mod 3:   0
Conserved:   ✓ BALANCED
\stopverb}

\p{This perfect 46/46/46 distribution enables optimal trifurcated parallel processing.}
}

\subtree{
\title{ACSet Schema (Geometric Morphism)}
\p{The translation from Info to Skill uses a geometric morphism \code{\startverb f: InfoTopos → SkillTopos\stopverb}:}

\pre{\startverb
Objects (Ob):
  Node      - Info nodes (sections, subsections)
  Edge      - Navigation and reference links
  Content   - Extracted text and code blocks

Morphisms (Hom):
  next: Node → Node     - Sequential navigation
  prev: Node → Node     - Backward navigation  
  up:   Node → Node     - Hierarchical parent
  menu: Node → Node     - Chapter/section containment
  xref: Node → Node     - Cross-references (*Note)

Attributes:
  trit: Node → GF(3)    - Deterministic color assignment
  text: Node → String   - Node content
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Integration with Gay.jl}
\p{The GF(3) coloring uses the same SplitMix64 hash as Gay.jl:}

\pre{\startverb
using Gay

# Color SICP nodes deterministically
for node in sicp_nodes
    seed = hash(node.id)
    color = gay_color(seed)  # Returns palette with GF(3) trit
    node.trit = color.trit
end

# Verify conservation
@assert sum(n.trit for n in sicp_nodes) % 3 == 0
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Commands}
\pre{\startverb
# Read in Emacs
info sicp

# Re-translate with geometric morphism
bb info_to_skill_morphism.bb translate sicp.info

# Verify grammar and GF(3) conservation
bb info_to_skill_morphism.bb verify sicp.info

# Parse to CRDT-style sexp
bb info_to_skill_morphism.bb parse sicp.info > sicp.sexp
\stopverb}
}

